{"type":"message","id":"a8e0c8ba","parentId":"15c4e63a","timestamp":"2026-04-17T12:13:16.035Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the problem now!\n\nIn the D:\\coam system:\n1. The `minimax` provider in models.json has `\"apiKey\": \"MINIMAX_API_KEY\"` - this is an **environment variable reference**, not the actual key\n2. The .env file has `MINIMAX_API_KEY=your-actual-minimax-key` (placeholder!)\n3. But auth-profiles.json has `minimax:cn` with the actual key - however, this is a **profile**, not directly linked to the provider\n\nThe Linux system has the same issue - models.json references `MINIMAX_API_KEY` env var, but the env var is also the placeholder. HOWEVER, in the Linux system, we tested the API directly with the key from auth-profiles.json and it worked.\n\nThe difference is: in Linux, we updated auth-profiles.json with the actual key, but the models.json still references the env var. So either:\n1. The env var was set but still shows placeholder (because the shell session wasn't updated)\n2. Or OpenClaw is reading from auth-profiles.json instead of the env var for some configurations\n\nFor D:\\coam, the situation is similar. The models.json says `apiKey: \"MINIMAX_API_KEY\"` but:\n1. The .env has the placeholder\n2. The auth-profiles.json has the actual key\n\nThe question is: which one is OpenClaw using?\n\nLet me check if there's an auth-state.json that might give clues:","thinkingSignature":"536ea8e68b679010edcb227d2b7675defb716f776aa4b0d31a97ce5cc315c036"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_pflju90w9ln3_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/mnt/d/coam/.openclaw/agents/main/agent/auth-state.json"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":40227,"output":352,"cacheRead":20856,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":61435,"cost":{"input":0.0120681,"output":0.00042239999999999997,"cacheRead":0.00125136,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.01374186}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestam